---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Deployment | BeaconGuard Regulated Enterprise Environments"
  description="BeaconGuard deploys alongside existing applications in regulated enterprise workflow environments as an inline policy enforcement boundary before model execution."
>
  <section class="stack-section">
    <h1>Deployment</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard is intended for regulated enterprise workflow environments where governance is part of runtime operations, not a later add-on.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Deployment Without System Replacement</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard is designed to deploy alongside existing applications. Existing systems continue to own workflow logic, records, case management, identity, logging, and compliance processes. BeaconGuard interposes at the AI request boundary to enforce policy before model execution and emit decision evidence afterward.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Deployment Scenarios</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Healthcare architecture evaluation</li>
      <li>Financial workflow evaluation</li>
      <li>Internal automation evaluation</li>
      <li>Sandbox policy simulation</li>
      <li>Non-production controlled validation</li>
      <li>Workflow-specific proof of concept</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard can be evaluated before production deployment using synthetic or de-identified workflow scenarios, deterministic metadata tags, mock request IDs, and representative policy schemas.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Placement and Intent</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard belongs in the runtime path between existing application services and AI/model endpoints. This ensures authorization-sensitive interaction is governed at the AI request boundary before the request reaches or consumes model outputs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Trust Boundaries and Operational Posture</h2>
    <p>
      Policy is authoritative at enforcement time within the inline runtime control boundary. Applications and downstream systems should not silently bypass governance outcomes. When required policy material, signed metadata, source-system trust, approved-pathway status, or freshness inputs are missing or invalid, decisions must fail closed or route for review.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Technical References</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/deployment-integration">Deployment and integration</a></li>
      <li><a href="/docs/compliance-audit">Compliance controls</a></li>
      <li><a href="/how-it-works">How BeaconGuard enforces decisions</a></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/contact">Discuss deployment needs</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/trust-assurance">Understand Trust Center boundaries</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
